<br>
You've planted the thing decades in advance of the dangerous close approach to Earth, so you mean for  it to keep operating; why shut it down, after the miss?<br>
Better yet, store &amp; save the chemicals, and use rock dust for reation mass from a mass driver. Plant enough fabrication equipment to make more rail length from parts brought along (90% plus of the mass driver's mass is structure like roled &amp; stamped metals, truss, or maybe concrete).<br>
As time goes on, the mass being pushed goes down, due to lost rock dust. Ices &amp; some metals get stored, and the Ev of the rocket goes up, making it better &amp; better.<br>
The close approach (which would have been a hit if you hadn't altered the rock's course) slings tohe rock/ships course to another close approach with Venus, which some years down the line, brings it back to the Earth, so it can be captured by an Earth/Moon/Earth series into HEEO.<br>
<br>
In short, any asteroid deflection we attempt entails nearly as much if not more infrastructure at the rock as a mine/tug, so why not stretch out your acquaintence with the rock, and make a few hundred billion$ from it?<br>
A wire mesh network ties the rock/aggregate jumble together to take the stresses, and allow you to move around the thing easily. Solar mirrors collect process heat &amp; electricity.<br>
NPR engine sections bring people and their habs and cargo to the rock (take the ship apart, and drop everything but the engine as payload).<br>
Until you can bootstrap up to building full-G habs with full radiation shielding, the NTR tug stages cycle crews back &amp; forth.<br>
<br>
This is really good. So little delta-V is needed, that a huge fraction of any mass placed in LEO is cargo to the destination, and trips take mere days or a few weeks at most with an NPR. Orion is nearly wasted on this mission, except that it does allow a huge cargo <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">and</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> quick trips.<br>
Absolutely no concerns for long-duration flight adverse health effects.<br>
